import pandas as pd 

# Read the CSV file with proper encoding and date parsing
df = pd.read_csv('C:/Users/JQE9675M2SSD512/[DeskPy/GlobalSuperstore/Store.csv', 
                 encoding='ISO-8859-1', 
                 parse_dates=['Order Date'], 
                 dayfirst=True)

#encoding='ISO-8859-1': This specifies that the file should be read using the ISO-8859-1 encoding, 
#which supports many Western European characters that might not be supported in UTF-8.

# 'Order Date' is in string format
# Standardize the 'Order Date' column
df['Order Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Order Date'], errors='coerce', dayfirst=True)

# Convert Sales and Profit columns to numeric (before resampling), in case they contain non-numeric values
df['Sales'] = pd.to_numeric(df['Sales'], errors='coerce')
df['Profit'] = pd.to_numeric(df['Profit'], errors='coerce')
df['Quantity'] = pd.to_numeric(df['Quantity'], errors='coerce')

Monthly Trend on Sales and Profit (Line Chart)¶

In [6]:
from bokeh.plotting import figure, show, output_notebook
from bokeh.models import ColumnDataSource, HoverTool
from bokeh.layouts import column
from bokeh.io import push_notebook

import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')




# Read the CSV file with proper encoding and date parsing
df = pd.read_csv('C:/Users/JQE9675M2SSD512/[DeskPy/GlobalSuperstore/Store.csv', 
                 encoding='ISO-8859-1', 
                 parse_dates=['Order Date'], 
                 dayfirst=True)

#encoding='ISO-8859-1': This specifies that the file should be read using the ISO-8859-1 encoding, 
#which supports many Western European characters that might not be supported in UTF-8.

# 'Order Date' is in string format
# Standardize the 'Order Date' column
df['Order Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Order Date'], errors='coerce', dayfirst=True)

# Convert Sales and Profit columns to numeric (before resampling), in case they contain non-numeric values
df['Sales'] = pd.to_numeric(df['Sales'], errors='coerce')
df['Profit'] = pd.to_numeric(df['Profit'], errors='coerce')
# Assuming df has an 'Order Date' column in datetime format
# Set 'Order Date' as the index
df.set_index('Order Date', inplace=True)

# Resample the data to monthly totals using 'M' (month-end)
monthly_totals = df.resample('M').agg({
    'Sales': 'sum',
    'Profit': 'sum'
})

# Format the index to 'Month-Year' for display purposes
monthly_totals.index = monthly_totals.index.to_period('M').strftime('%b-%Y')

# Convert the index to a datetime format for plotting
monthly_totals['Month-Year'] = pd.to_datetime(monthly_totals.index)

# Create a ColumnDataSource from the DataFrame for interactive Bokeh plotting
source = ColumnDataSource(monthly_totals)

# Create a new figure for the line chart
p = figure(x_axis_type="datetime", 
           title="Monthly Sales and Profit",
           width=1400, height=500)  # Updated to width and height

# Add Sales line
p.line('Month-Year', 'Sales', source=source, line_width=2, color="blue", legend_label="Monthly Sales")
p.circle('Month-Year', 'Sales', source=source, fill_color="blue", size=6)

# Add Profit line
p.line('Month-Year', 'Profit', source=source, line_width=2, color="green", legend_label="Monthly Profit")
p.circle('Month-Year', 'Profit', source=source, fill_color="green", size=6)

# Customize the layout
p.xaxis.axis_label = "Month-Year"
p.yaxis.axis_label = "Amount"
p.xaxis.major_label_orientation = 3.14 / 4  # Rotate x-axis labels

# Add hover tool for interactivity
hover = HoverTool(tooltips=[("Date", "@{Month-Year}{%b-%Y}"),
                            ("Sales", "@Sales{0,0.00}"),
                            ("Profit", "@Profit{0,0.00}")],
                  formatters={'@{Month-Year}': 'datetime'},
                  mode='vline')
p.add_tools(hover)

# Finalize layout and show plot
p.legend.location = "top_left"
p.legend.click_policy = "hide"  # Allows for clicking to hide lines
output_notebook()  # Ensure output shows in Jupyter Notebook or similar
show(p, notebook_handle=True)

Sales and Profits Trend of Technology, Furniture, and Office Supplies¶

In [7]:
# Read the CSV file with proper encoding and date parsing
df = pd.read_csv('C:/Users/JQE9675M2SSD512/[DeskPy/GlobalSuperstore/Store.csv', 
                 encoding='ISO-8859-1', 
                 parse_dates=['Order Date'], 
                 dayfirst=True)

#encoding='ISO-8859-1': This specifies that the file should be read using the ISO-8859-1 encoding, 
#which supports many Western European characters that might not be supported in UTF-8.

# 'Order Date' is in string format
# Standardize the 'Order Date' column
df['Order Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Order Date'], errors='coerce', dayfirst=True)

# Convert Sales and Profit columns to numeric (before resampling), in case they contain non-numeric values
df['Sales'] = pd.to_numeric(df['Sales'], errors='coerce')
df['Profit'] = pd.to_numeric(df['Profit'], errors='coerce')

# Extract month and year from 'Order Date' for grouping
df['YearMonth'] = df['Order Date'].dt.to_period('M')

# Group the data by YearMonth and Category, summing up Sales and Profit
monthly_trends = df.groupby(['YearMonth', 'Category'])[['Sales', 'Profit']].sum().reset_index()

# Convert YearMonth to datetime for Bokeh plotting
monthly_trends['YearMonth'] = pd.to_datetime(monthly_trends['YearMonth'].astype(str))

# Define the categories
categories = ['Technology', 'Furniture', 'Office Supplies']

# Create a list to hold the figures for each category
plots = []

# Create separate interactive plots for each category
for category in categories:
    # Filter data for the current category
    subset = monthly_trends[monthly_trends['Category'] == category]
    source = ColumnDataSource(subset)

    # Create a new figure for each category
    p = figure(x_axis_type="datetime", 
               title=f"Monthly Trend of Sales and Profit for {category}",
               width=1400, height=600)
    
    # Add Sales line for the category
    p.line('YearMonth', 'Sales', source=source, line_width=2, color="blue", legend_label="Sales")
    p.circle('YearMonth', 'Sales', source=source, color="blue", size=6)
    
    # Add Profit line for the category
    p.line('YearMonth', 'Profit', source=source, line_width=2, color="green", legend_label="Profit")
    p.circle('YearMonth', 'Profit', source=source, color="green", size=6)
    
    # Customize axes and title
    p.xaxis.axis_label = "Month-Year"
    p.yaxis.axis_label = "Amount"
    p.xaxis.major_label_orientation = 3.14 / 4  # Rotate x-axis labels
    
    # Add hover tool for interactivity
    hover = HoverTool(tooltips=[("Date", "@YearMonth{%b-%Y}"),
                                ("Sales", "@Sales{0,0.00}"),
                                ("Profit", "@Profit{0,0.00}")],
                      formatters={'@YearMonth': 'datetime'},
                      mode='vline')
    p.add_tools(hover)
    
    # Set legend location and click policy
    p.legend.location = "top_left"
    p.legend.click_policy = "hide"
    
    # Append plot to the list
    plots.append(p)

# Display all plots in a column layout
output_notebook()  # Ensure output shows in Jupyter Notebook or similar
show(column(*plots), notebook_handle=True)

Sales Trend of Subcategories under their Respective Categories (Line Chart)¶

In [8]:
from bokeh.palettes import Category20  # Import a color palette

# Create a new column 'Month-Year' for easier grouping (YYYY-MM format)
df['Month-Year'] = df['Order Date'].dt.to_period('M')

# Group by 'Category', 'Sub-Category', and 'Month-Year', and sum the 'Sales'
grouped_data = df.groupby(['Category', 'Sub-Category', 'Month-Year'])['Sales'].sum().reset_index()

# Convert 'Month-Year' to datetime for Bokeh plotting
grouped_data['Month-Year'] = pd.to_datetime(grouped_data['Month-Year'].astype(str))

# Get unique categories
categories = df['Category'].unique()

# Create a list to hold the figures for each category
plots = []

# Create separate interactive line charts for each 'Category'
for category in categories:
    # Filter data for the current category
    category_data = grouped_data[grouped_data['Category'] == category]

    # Create a new figure for each category
    p = figure(x_axis_type="datetime", 
               title=f"Monthly Sales Trend for {category}",
               width=1400, height=600)

    # Get unique sub-categories and assign different colors
    sub_categories = category_data['Sub-Category'].unique()
    colors = Category20[len(sub_categories)]  # Use Bokeh's Category20 palette

    # Iterate over the sub-categories and plot each one with a unique color
    for i, sub_category in enumerate(sub_categories):
        sub_category_data = category_data[category_data['Sub-Category'] == sub_category]
        source = ColumnDataSource(sub_category_data)

        # Add a line trace for each sub-category with its own color
        p.line('Month-Year', 'Sales', source=source, line_width=2, color=colors[i], legend_label=sub_category)
        p.circle('Month-Year', 'Sales', source=source, size=6, color=colors[i], legend_label=sub_category)

    # Customize axes and title
    p.xaxis.axis_label = "Month-Year"
    p.yaxis.axis_label = "Sales"
    p.xaxis.major_label_orientation = 3.14 / 4  # Rotate x-axis labels

    # Add hover tool for interactivity
    hover = HoverTool(tooltips=[("Date", "@{Month-Year}{%b-%Y}"), 
                                ("Sales", "@Sales{0,0.00}"),
                                ("Sub-Category", "@{Sub-Category}")], #{} since Sub-Category has a special character (-)
                      formatters={'@{Month-Year}': 'datetime'},
                      mode='vline')
    p.add_tools(hover)

    # Set legend properties
    p.legend.title = 'Sub-Category'
    p.legend.location = "top_left"
    p.legend.click_policy = "hide"  # Allows toggling sub-category lines

    # Append plot to the list
    plots.append(p)

# Display all plots in a column layout
output_notebook()  # Ensure output shows in Jupyter Notebook or similar
show(column(*plots), notebook_handle=True)

'''from bokeh.plotting import figure, show
from bokeh.io import output_notebook
from bokeh.models import ColumnDataSource
from bokeh.layouts import column
from bokeh.palettes import Category10'''

# Set output to notebook (or you can use output_file("your_file.html") for saving as HTML)
#output_notebook()

# Create a new column 'Month-Year' for grouping by month
df['Month-Year'] = df['Order Date'].dt.to_period('M')

# Group by 'Sub-Category' and 'Month-Year', summing up Sales and Profit
grouped_data = df.groupby(['Sub-Category', 'Month-Year']).agg({'Sales': 'sum', 'Profit': 'sum'}).reset_index()

# Get unique Sub-Categories
sub_categories = grouped_data['Sub-Category'].unique()

# Create a list to hold all figures
figures = []

# Create separate interactive plots for each Sub-Category
for sub_category in sub_categories:
    sub_category_data = grouped_data[grouped_data['Sub-Category'] == sub_category]

    # Create a new figure for each Sub-Category
    fig = figure(title=f'Monthly Sales and Profit Trend for {sub_category}',
                 x_axis_label='Month-Year',
                 y_axis_label='Amount',
                 x_axis_type='datetime',
                 width=1400,  # Corrected attribute
                 height=600)  # Corrected attribute

    # Convert 'Month-Year' to datetime for plotting
    sub_category_data['Month-Year'] = sub_category_data['Month-Year'].dt.to_timestamp()

    # Create a ColumnDataSource for easier data handling
    source = ColumnDataSource(sub_category_data)

    # Add HoverTool
    hover = HoverTool()
    hover.tooltips = [
        ("Month-Year", "@{Month-Year}{%b %Y}"),  # Format Month-Year
        ("Sales", "@Sales{0,0}"),                # Format Sales
        ("Profit", "@Profit{0,0}")                # Format Profit
    ]
    hover.formatters = {'@{Month-Year}': 'datetime'}  # Specify datetime formatting
    fig.add_tools(hover)

    # Add Sales line
    fig.line('Month-Year', 'Sales', source=source, line_width=2, color='blue', legend_label=f'{sub_category} - Sales', line_dash='solid')
    fig.circle('Month-Year', 'Sales', source=source, size=6, color='blue')

    # Add Profit line
    fig.line('Month-Year', 'Profit', source=source, line_width=2, color='green', legend_label=f'{sub_category} - Profit', line_dash='dashed')
    fig.square('Month-Year', 'Profit', source=source, size=6, color='green')

    # Customize legend
    fig.legend.title = f'{sub_category} - Metrics'
    fig.legend.location = "top_left"

    # Rotate x-axis labels for better readability
    fig.xaxis.major_label_orientation = 45

    # Add figure to the list
    figures.append(fig)

# Display all figures in a column layout
show(column(*figures))

from math import pi

from bokeh.transform import cumsum
from bokeh.models import ColumnDataSource, LabelSet, NumeralTickFormatter, HoverTool

import textwrap

# Ensure plots display inline in the notebook
output_notebook()

'''# Read the CSV file with proper encoding and date parsing
df = pd.read_csv('C:/Users/JQE9675M2SSD512/[DeskPy/GlobalSuperstore/Store.csv', 
                 encoding='ISO-8859-1',

# Standardize the 'Order Date' column
df['Order Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Order Date'], errors='coerce', dayfirst=True)

# ----------------------------- Donut Chart -----------------------------
# Group by 'Category' and sum the 'Sales'
grouped_data = df.groupby('Category')['Sales'].sum().reset_index()

# Define category colors
category_colors = {
    'Technology': '#1f77b4',
    'Furniture': '#ff7f0e',
    'Office Supplies': '#2ca02c'
}

# Prepare the data for the donut chart
grouped_data['angle'] = grouped_data['Sales'] / grouped_data['Sales'].sum() * 2 * pi

# Map colors based on category
grouped_data['color'] = grouped_data['Category'].map(category_colors)

# Create the donut chart
#tooltips=[("Category", "@category"), ("Sub-Category", "@label"), ("Sales", "@sales{$0,0.00}")]
donut_chart = figure(title="Total Sales by Category", tools="hover", 
                     tooltips=[("Category", "@Category"), ("Sales", "@Sales{$0,0.00}")], 
                     x_range=(-1, 1), y_range=(-1, 1))

#donut_chart = figure(title="Total Sales by Category", tools="hover", tooltips="@Category: @$name", 
#                     x_range=(-1, 1), y_range=(-1, 1))


# Draw the wedges
donut_chart.wedge(x=0, y=0, radius=0.4, start_angle=cumsum('angle', include_zero=True), 
                  end_angle=cumsum('angle'), line_color="white", fill_color='color', 
                  legend_field='Category', source=ColumnDataSource(grouped_data))



# Add a hole in the center
donut_chart.circle(0, 0, radius=0.2, color="white")

# Show the donut chart
show(donut_chart)




# ----------------------------- Treemap -----------------------------

# Group by 'Category' and 'Sub-Category' and sum Sales
grouped_data = df.groupby(['Category', 'Sub-Category'])['Sales'].sum().reset_index()

# Set up category colors
category_colors = {'Technology': '#1f77b4', 'Furniture': '#ff7f0e', 'Office Supplies': '#2ca02c'}
grouped_data['Color'] = grouped_data['Category'].map(category_colors)

# Define function to wrap text
def wrap_label(text, width=20):
    return "\n".join(textwrap.wrap(text, width=width))

grouped_data['Wrapped Label'] = grouped_data['Sub-Category'].apply(wrap_label)

# Set up data for hierarchical positioning
total_sales = grouped_data['Sales'].sum()
x, y = 0, 0  # Initial coordinates
rectangles = []

# Loop through categories for column-based positioning
for category, category_data in grouped_data.groupby('Category'):
    category_sales = category_data['Sales'].sum()
    category_width = category_sales / total_sales  # Proportional width for the category
    sub_x, sub_y = x, y  # Start coordinates for sub-categories within this category
    
    for _, row in category_data.iterrows():
        height = row['Sales'] / category_sales  # Height of each sub-category within its category
        rectangles.append((sub_x, sub_y, category_width, height, row['Wrapped Label'], row['Color'], category, row['Sales']))
        sub_y += height  # Move y up for the next sub-category within the column

    x += category_width  # Move x to the next column for the next category

# Create Bokeh figure
p = figure(title="Treemap of Sales by Category and Sub-Category", width=1200, height=1200, tools="")

# Prepare data for rectangles
source = ColumnDataSource(data=dict(
    x=[x + width / 2 for x, _, width, _, _, _, _, _ in rectangles],
    y=[y + height / 2 for _, y, _, height, _, _, _, _ in rectangles],
    width=[width for _, _, width, _, _, _, _, _ in rectangles],
    height=[height for _, _, _, height, _, _, _, _ in rectangles],
    color=[color for _, _, _, _, _, color, _, _ in rectangles],
    label=[label for _, _, _, _, label, _, _, _ in rectangles],
    category=[category for _, _, _, _, _, _, category, _ in rectangles],
    sales=[sales for _, _, _, _, _, _, _, sales in rectangles],
))

# Draw rectangles
p.rect(x='x', y='y', width='width', height='height', fill_color='color', line_color="black", source=source)

# Add hover tool
hover = HoverTool(tooltips=[("Category", "@category"), ("Sub-Category", "@label"), ("Sales", "@sales{$0,0.00}")])
p.add_tools(hover)

# Add labels for sub-categories
labels = LabelSet(x='x', y='y', text='label', source=source, text_align='center', text_font_size="10pt")
p.add_layout(labels)

# Hide axes
p.xaxis.visible = False
p.yaxis.visible = False

# Show plot
show(p)

# List of markets
markets = df['Market'].unique()

# Plot a separate chart for each market
for market in markets:
    # Filter data for the current market
    market_data = df[df['Market'] == market]
    
    # Group by Sub-Category and sum Sales
    subcategory_sales = market_data.groupby('Sub-Category')['Sales'].sum().sort_values(ascending=False)
    
    # Create the plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 3))
    
    # Bar chart
    plt.bar(subcategory_sales.index, subcategory_sales.values, color='skyblue')
    
    # Add labels and title
    plt.title(f'Total Sales of Sub-Categories in {market}', fontsize=14)

Sales of Sub-categories on Consumer Type¶

# List of segments
segments = df['Segment'].unique()

# Plot a separate chart for each segment
for segment in segments:
    # Filter data for the current segment
    segment_data = df[df['Segment'] == segment]
    
    # Group by Sub-Category and sum Sales
    subcategory_sales = segment_data.groupby('Sub-Category')['Sales'].sum().sort_values(ascending=False)
    
    # Create the plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    
    # Bar chart
    plt.bar(subcategory_sales.index, subcategory_sales.values, color='lightcoral')
    
    # Add labels and title
    plt.title(f'Total Sales of Sub-Categories in {segment}', fontsize=14)
    #plt.xlabel('Sub-Category', fontsize=12)
    #plt.ylabel('Total Sales', fontsize=12)
    
    # Rotate x-axis labels for better readability
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
    
    # Show the plot
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
